docs\devlog\detailed\2026-04-25_2026-04-25.md-122-
docs\devlog\detailed\2026-04-25_2026-04-25.md:123:**Reasoning:** Opus's H_NEW1 finding showed listener throws inside `processCommands` bypassed `finalizeTickFailure` because `runTick`'s outer try-finally has no catch. The simplest fix that keeps engine invariants intact is to isolate listener errors in the emit methods themselves — the engine has done its job (commands ran/were dropped per the existing contract), and a listener bug shouldn't corrupt that. Matches the conventional sync pub/sub pattern. The `console.warn` for poisoned API access aligns with user decision Q3 ("stay available but raise a warning"); the once-per-cycle dedup prevents log spam from agents that hit the poisoned world repeatedly without calling `recover()`.
docs\devlog\detailed\2026-04-25_2026-04-25.md-124-
docs\devlog\detailed\2026-04-25_2026-04-25.md-125-**Notes:**
docs\devlog\detailed\2026-04-25_2026-04-25.md-126-
docs\devlog\detailed\2026-04-25_2026-04-25.md:127:- The diff-listener loop's existing try/catch (which routes to `finalizeTickFailure` with phase `'listeners'`) is intentionally left as-is. It is the one path where a listener error legitimately poisons the world, because by that point the engine has finished its tick and the failure surface is the listener phase itself. The other three listener paths fire mid-tick or right after a real failure, where listener bugs are not engine bugs.
