docs\reviews\full\2026-04-25\2\raw\opus.md-20-### Listener exceptions during `processCommands` bypass the fail-fast/poison contract
docs\reviews\full\2026-04-25\2\raw\opus.md-21-- **File**: `src/world.ts:1471-1543` (`processCommands`), `src/world.ts:1545-1573` (`dropPendingCommands`), `src/world.ts:1843-1858` (`emitCommandExecution`)
docs\reviews\full\2026-04-25\2\raw\opus.md:22:- **Problem**: `processCommands` calls `this.emitCommandExecution(...)` from four sites: (a) line 1476 in the missing-handler branch, (b) line 1501 inside the success try-block, (c) line 1511 inside the catch on handler throws, and (d) inside `dropPendingCommands` for every aborted command. Sites (a) and (d) are NOT inside any try/catch. If a registered `commandExecutionListener` throws synchronously (which user code is allowed to do — there's no documented or enforced "listeners must not throw" contract), the throw propagates up through `processCommands` → `runTick` → `executeTickOrThrow`. `runTick`'s outer `try` (line 1335) only has a `finally`, no `catch`, so `finalizeTickFailure` is never called: `this.poisoned` stays `null`, `this.lastTickFailure` is left at whatever its previous value was, `gameLoop.tick` is not advanced, and `currentDiff`/`currentMetrics` from the prior tick stay in place. The world has been partially mutated (commands before the listener throw ran their handlers, eventBus was cleared, dirty flags were cleared) but is not flagged as poisoned. Subsequent `step()` calls happily run a new tick on top of this inconsistent state.
docs\reviews\full\2026-04-25\2\raw\opus.md-23-- **Why it matters**: The whole point of the v0.4.0 "poisoned world" contract — and the prominent ARCHITECTURE.md / api-reference.md / changelog claims about fail-fast — is that any tick-pipeline failure marks the world as poisoned. A `commandExecutionListener` that throws is the easiest way for a user (or a misbehaving renderer/history adapter) to silently break that contract. The `tickFailureListener` path in `emitTickFailure` (line 1646-1650, called from `finalizeTickFailure`) has the same problem: if a `tickFailureListener` throws, the throw replaces the original `WorldTickFailureError` on its way out, the failure that was being reported is lost, and although `this.poisoned` was set before the emit, `finalizeTickFailure` itself does not complete (it never returns the cloned failure to the caller).
docs\reviews\full\2026-04-25\2\raw\opus.md:24:- **Suggested fix**: Wrap the listener iteration in a try/catch that swallows or, better, collects listener errors into a synthetic listener-phase `TickFailure` so the contract still holds. Concretely, `emitCommandExecutionResult` and `emitTickFailure` should isolate listener exceptions (e.g. log or accumulate them, never let them re-enter the pipeline). The diff-listener loop in `runTick` (line 1442-1460) already does this — apply the same pattern to the other two.
