docs\reviews\full\2026-04-25\2\raw\opus.md:40:### Tick-failure listeners receive an unsafe deep clone (now ok), but `getLastTickFailure` does too — every read JSON-clones
docs\reviews\full\2026-04-25\2\raw\opus.md-41-- **File**: `src/world.ts:980-982` (`getLastTickFailure`), `src/world.ts:2228-2230` (`cloneTickFailure`)
docs\reviews\full\2026-04-25\2\raw\opus.md:42:- **Problem**: `getLastTickFailure()` runs `JSON.parse(JSON.stringify(failure))` on every call. A diff-listener or history recorder polling this between ticks (or inside the listener loop while debugging) pays the full clone cost per call, even though `failure` is immutable from the engine's perspective. The clone is the right default for safety, but the cost is non-trivial: `TickFailure` includes the full error stack trace. The cheaper option used elsewhere (e.g., `getDiff`, `getMetrics`) is fine here because diff/metrics are heavyweight; `lastTickFailure` is lightweight but called often by history/scenario tooling.
docs\reviews\full\2026-04-25\2\raw\opus.md-43-- **Why it matters**: Minor perf trap for AI-agent operators that loop on `world.getLastTickFailure()` checking for failures. Not urgent but worth a comment or a memoized clone.
docs\reviews\full\2026-04-25\2\raw\opus.md-44-- **Suggested fix**: Cache the cloned failure in a private field, invalidated whenever `lastTickFailure` is reassigned (or when `recover()` runs). Or just freeze the constructed `TickFailure` and return it directly — it's already JSON-safe by construction (line 1685-1706 asserts).
