docs\reviews\full\2026-04-25\1\raw\opus.md-39-### `submit()` pushes commands without a `submissionSequence` in the fast path, breaking client correlation
docs\reviews\full\2026-04-25\1\raw\opus.md-40-- **File**: `src/world.ts:616-629`, `src/world.ts:1393-1429`, `src/client-adapter.ts:144-163`
docs\reviews\full\2026-04-25\1\raw\opus.md:41:- **Problem**: In the non-`full`/no-listeners fast path, `submit()` calls `this.commandQueue.push(type, data)` without any `submissionSequence`. When the handler later runs, `emitCommandExecution` produces `submissionSequence: null`. `ClientAdapter.commandExecutionListener` immediately returns when `result.submissionSequence === null` (line 145), so the client never receives `commandExecuted`/`commandFailed` for those commands. The same command issued via `submitWithResult()` would be correlated.
docs\reviews\full\2026-04-25\1\raw\opus.md-42-- **Why it matters**: Whether a command is observable on the wire depends on which submission API was used and which instrumentation profile is active — a non-obvious cross-cut that any AI agent or remote client has to reverse-engineer.
docs\reviews\full\2026-04-25\1\raw\opus.md:43:- **Suggested fix**: Always assign a sequence in `submit()` (and have `submitWithResult` reuse the same path) regardless of profile. The cost is a single `nextCommandResultSequence++`. Reserve listener-free fast paths for emission, not sequence assignment.
